  "event_preview": "Charlotte Motor Speedway is a 1.5-mile (2.414 km) quad-oval in Concord, North Carolina, opened in 1960 with 24-degree banking in the turns and 5-degree banking on the straights. The Coca-Cola 600 is the thirteenth race of the 2026 NASCAR Cup Series season and the longest race on the calendar, contested over 400 laps (600 miles) with stage breaks at laps 100 and 200. The race is held Sunday at 6 p.m. ET on Memorial Day weekend and will be broadcast on Prime Video, HBO Max, PRN Radio and SiriusXM NASCAR Radio. Ross Chastain is the defending winner, having claimed glory in the 2025 running with a late-race pass on William Byron. Katherine Legge, entered in the No. 78 Live Fast Motorsports Chevrolet, is attempting to become the sixth driver and first female to complete the iconic \"Double\" — competing in both the Indianapolis 500 and the Coca-Cola 600 on the same day in pursuit of 1,100 miles of racing.\n\nThe all-time Cup Series qualifying record at Charlotte belongs to Elliott Sadler, who turned a 27.948-second lap at 193.216 mph on October 13, 2005. The race average speed record is held by Martin Truex Jr., who completed the 2016 Coca-Cola 600 at 160.644 mph en route to victory — a mark that stands as the fastest-ever pace in the event's history at the 1.5-mile oval."
}
